In this article, President Barack Obama proclaims December as National Impaired Driving Prevention Month. The article emphasizes the importance of celebrating the holiday season safely and highlights the dangers of drunk, drugged, and distracted driving, which cause thousands of accidents and deaths each year. The administration aims to raise public awareness, improve screening procedures for impaired driving, and provide law enforcement officers with necessary training. The article also emphasizes the role of families, educators, healthcare providers, and community leaders in preventing impaired driving by educating young people about the risks and promoting responsible decision-making. The president urges all Americans to make responsible decisions and take appropriate measures to prevent impaired driving.